[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating OSGi interfaces**\n\nI'm considering the implications of using old OSGi 4.0 interfaces alongside org.osgi.core 4.2.0. It seems that if I don't implement new methods, compilation might fail, especially if the classpath prioritizes old over new interfaces. There's a potential for class shadowing with native images, too. I'm weighing whether to establish a setup beyond a typical test scaffold before achieving meaningful coverage. However, it seems that local verification for this setup may not be necessary. I'll explore testing through javap instead.\n\n**Considering OSGi setup guidelines**\n\nI’m thinking about including \"agent_guidance\" for OSGi-specific coverage. Using a lightweight mock Bundle/BundleContext means we don't need a real OSGi container or Docker. They want to know if we should offer setup guidance — I guess a note saying no environment or system properties are needed would work. It looks like the deterministic setup involves only org.osgi.core. However, if the POM has changed packaging from bundle to jar, I need to consider potential risks from duplicate API jars. Also, should I include provided dependencies like mail/jaxb in the deterministic setup?\n\n**Assessing library coverage setup**\n\nI’m considering how the normal generated test scaffold works when creating a PR for updating an existing library version. It typically uses current tests and the existing build.gradle file. Now, I need to decide if the library requires any additional setup beyond the usual scaffold to ensure meaningful coverage. Research shows that Jersey-core has provided dependencies for mail, jaxb, and osgi. So, if the scaffold only adds the library, I might need to include these dependencies to cover MIME, JAXB, and OSGi properly.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_07ec014a4b49e23b016a42b2f35d7c8190af87a96996c6e16a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],